  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>Consider the voting system <m>[25 | 24, 20, 1]</m>.</p>
    </introduction>

    <task xml:id="voting-shapley-shubik-homework1">
      <statement>
        <p>Calculate the percentage of the total weight that each voter holds.</p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>53.3%, 44.4%, 2.2%</p>
      </answer>
    </task>

    <task xml:id="voting-shapley-shubik-homework2">
      <statement>
        <p>Calculate the Shapley–Shubik Power Index for each voter.</p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>0.60, 0.20, 0.20</p>
      </answer>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>Comparing your answers to parts <xref ref="voting-shapley-shubik-homework1" text="local"/> and <xref ref="voting-shapley-shubik-homework2" text="local"/>, explain why weight is not the same as power.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          For example, <m>P_2</m> has twenty times more weight than <m>P_3</m>, but the same power.
          Also, <m>P_1</m> has three times as much power as <m>P_2</m>, even though the weights are close.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exercise>

